An unprecedented future
JERUSALEM – With my now almost 90 years of life, I cannot recall a time when the past was so insignificant for political decision-making.
No significant development of the present was predicted by anyone beforehand.
Experts studied the past, but because they were trapped in old paradigms, they could not derive the future from it.
Due to the dynamic complexity of today's world, in which, in the face of a scientifically based and rapidly changing global economy, more events are interdependent than ever before, we are unable to predict the future based on a linear extrapolation of the past.
The only certainty is that the future will be determined by scientific progress and innovation, which cannot be known in advance.
As a result of these developments, the traditional power of states and state leaders is declining. In today's globalized economy, it is not politicians, but innovators who exert the greatest influence.
The globalized economy affects all states, yet no single state can determine the outcome, because science and technology are boundless.
Global operating companies want to pursue their business worldwide, thereby causing, on the one hand, a loss of sovereignty, but on the other hand, weakening racism and prejudices, as well as, significantly, nationalism.
Due to this change, the fate of this world now lies in the hands of a younger generation. They are more technologically skilled than their parents and are connected to each other through social networks that overcome national borders, language barriers, or different forms of government.
The young founders of Facebook and Google exert greater global influence than many heads of state and generals.
These young people also form the vanguard of emerging political protest movements.
The "Arab Spring," the tent demonstrations in Israel, Occupy Wall Street, and the protests in Russia mark not a clash of cultures, but a battle of generations.
The younger generation knows that the way states and economies are currently being run is unsuitable for the new era.
Yet there are political "free-riders" who wish to exploit this latest awakening. However, not by advancing an agenda of freedom, but by introducing new forms of coercion.
In the Arab world, mainly Islamist extremists appropriate the protests of the younger generation for themselves, thereby stealing the revolution from them.
Israel has positively responded to the will of the younger generation, but it can and should not interfere in the events of the Arab world.
We are in the heart of the rebellious youth and their legitimate longing for freedom and fundamental rights, which are supposed to enable them to make themselves heard, choose their political leadership, and provide for their livelihood.
Israelis are waiting for the day when their country will no longer be the only democracy in the region, because the existence as an island of prosperity in the midst of a sea of poverty is unnatural.
Yet there is a serious concern that politically well-organized extremists are trying to win control over less well-organized liberals in elections, thereby preventing peace and stability.
Radical fundamentalists cannot offer real solutions to the fundamental problems of the region.
The current social upheavals threaten their way of life, which also includes the discrimination of women and a ban on modern education.
However, only fundamental reforms of established authority can pave the way towards freedom and growth.
Israel can serve as an example for others in achieving economic prosperity and social freedom, because its success is based on the fact that the country had absolutely nothing at the beginning.
When we returned to our homeland, we were rich in history but poor in natural resources.
We could rely only on our human capital.
Therefore, we invested in education and science. For this reason, we today have the highest percentage of scientists and patents per capita.
About 95 percent of our agriculture is based on high technology.
We use less water and yet achieve higher crop yields per square meter of arable land than any other country in the world.
What Israel achieves, others can also create.
We are gladly willing to offer our help wherever it is desired.
Together and in peace with our neighbors, we can shape a region of hope, development, and success.
Foremost, we must do everything in our power to end the conflict with the Palestinians.
Israel was not created to rule over another people, and this is not Israel's purpose.
We are genuinely interested in the creation of a Palestinian state that exists peacefully and side by side with Israel - the democratic state of the Jewish people.
For us, peace is both a moral imperative and a national security strategy, because resolving the conflict would help stabilize the region by neutralizing extremists who seek to manipulate citizen movements to advance their radical agenda.
The international community can support these efforts by offering incentives to those countries that strive for freedom and progress.
At the same time, decisive and pioneering political measures must be taken against the extremists.
Particularly Iran is a source of moral degradation, where extremism is promoted and reforms are blocked. They crush legitimate protests of their own citizens and work against the brave Syrians who are currently fighting for their freedom.
In addition, Iran uses multiple proxies to incite terrorism against moderate forces in the Palestinian Authority, in Lebanon, and in Iraq.
If Iran succeeds in acquiring nuclear weapons, the leaders of the country could shake the Near and Middle East and incite even more extremism and violence.
Israel will defend itself if Iran continues to demand the destruction of Israel.
Yet it is not only Israel that is threatened. Iran is a danger to peace and stability around the world.
The democracies of the world have declared that they will not allow Iran to acquire nuclear weapons. It is their duty to fulfill this commitment before it is no longer possible.
Beyond these immediate challenges, we all have the duty to fundamentally change the way we prepare our children to deal with the world today.
At a time when the past has become irrelevant for predicting the future, education must offer all children the opportunity to fully realize their potential.
Today's teachers should motivate our children toward creativity and innovation.
Self-realization is just as important as free speech
I am writing this article at the age of 88, but not because I have learned from experience.
On the contrary: experience is overvalued and often stifles the courage needed to face the future and create an unprecedented new world.
The future is already here. Looking back has no meaning.
